[1]
Date: Thu, 19 May 2005
From: Charlie Calisher <calisher@cybersafe.net>

The flap in "Unexplained deaths, canines - USA (multistate) (02)"
(20050519.1371) was necessary. This recurring problem, in ProMED postings
and elsewhere, is the result of sloppy usage. You are not alone if you use
the word "flu" for just about everything except paralytic diseases, but you
are not correct. Dengue and scores of other illnesses have been described
as "a mild flu-like illness". Those who define an illness as such likely
have never had one.
Athletes taking a day or 2 off usually are described as having "the flu",
which means they have diarrhea from eating too much or poorly, have a
hangover, or have a headache and a fever. Had they had influenza, they
would not be back on the field or court or rink within a day or 2, as
anyone who has had influenza can attest.
When describing hantaviral infections, it is frequently said that the
patient had "flu-like symptoms". Influenza ("flu") is clinically diagnosed
as a combination of fever, myalgias, and malaise plus cough and nasal
discharge, but patients with hantavirus pulmonary syndrome do not manifest
upper respiratory symptoms early in their illnesses. When a patient with
hantavirus pulmonary syndrome begins to cough, it is because of pulmonary
edema. Therefore, a patient with fever, myalgias, and malaise _without_
cough and nasal discharge do not have "a flu-like illness without cough and
nasal discharge"; they have something else.
The taxonomy of Influenza A virus, a prime cause of influenza (or, if one
must, "flu"), is a member of the family _Orthomyxoviridae_, genus
_Influenzavirus A_. Period. Proper communication requires proper usage of
terms and, one would hope, more exacting terms than are used by athletes,
lay periodicals, and other forms of mass communication. Calling everything
under the sun "flu" is a disservice to everyone, whether the subject is a
dog, a horse, a chicken, a human, or any other vertebrate.
The best resolution is to never use the term "flu" at all but, instead, use
the appropriate word or term, whatever that may be.
--
Charles H. Calisher, Ph.D.
Professor, Arthropod-borne and Infectious Diseases Laboratory
Department of Microbiology, Immunology and Pathology
College of Veterinary Medicine and Biomedical Sciences
Colorado State University
Ft. Collins, CO 80523
<calisher@cybercell.net>
[For recent subscribers, Dr. Calisher is a former viral disease moderator
for ProMED-mail and is known for his adherence to semantics (among other
things). - Mod.MPP]
